I have a proposal for a new extension to the `ContentManager`:

```
public abstract class ContentOptions
{
};

public class ContentManager
{
   public virtual T Load<T>(string assetName, ContentOptions options)
}
```

This is not for working around the content pipeline.  We wouldn't use this or recommend it be used to do runtime processing of content.  This is simply for passing options that are simple runtime choices down thru the ContentManager and down to the various content readers.

For example it could be used for textures:

```
var options = new TextureOptions();
options.sRGBFormat = true;
options.PreserveSystemCopy = true;
var texture = contentManager.Load<Texture2D>("myTexture",options);
```

sRGB support is simply creating the Texture2D using an sRGB format...  no extra processing is done.  While you could add support into a custom texture processor...  it is sort of overkill for something that is a runtime choice.

The issues with supporting Texture2D.GetData() on some platforms is easily solved by keeping around the system memory copy of the texture data.  By default the ContentManager throws that away after creating the GPU texture resource.  If for example we kept these around we could use them to implement a fast GetData() on textures.

